<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-extending-complex-functions">
  <title>Extending functions to the complex plane</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Extend familiar real functions to complex inputs and analyze their behavior.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Interpret complex outputs through domain coloring and mappings of planar regions.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Understand multivalued functions using principal branches and Riemann surfaces.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Mostly focuses on what happens if you plug a complex number into well-known functions.
        For all of these, view their domain coloring, and some important mappings of planar regions.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Exponential functions:
        <aside>
          <p>
            The exponential function is used to define pretty much all the other functions!
          </p>
        </aside>
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\ee^z \amp = \ee^{x+\ii y}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \ee^{x}\ee^{\ii y}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \ee^{x}\cos y + \ii\ee^{x}\sin y</mrow>
      </md>

      <p>
        Is now <m>2\uppi\ii</m> periodic in the imaginary direction!
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Trigonometric functions:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\sin z \amp = \frac{\ee^{\ii z}-\ee^{-\ii z}}{2\ii} = \sin x \cosh y + \ii\cos x\sinh y</mrow>
        <mrow>\cos z \amp = \frac{\ee^{\ii z}+\ee^{-\ii z}}{2} = \cos x \cosh y - \ii\sin x\sinh y</mrow>
      </md>

      <p>
        All other trigonometric functions are defined based on these.
        Also, we can actually find solutions to equations like <m>\sin z=5</m> now!
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Hyperbolic functions:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\sinh z \amp = \frac{\ee^{z}-\ee^{-z}}{2} = \sinh x \cos y + \ii\cosh x\sin y</mrow>
        <mrow>\cosh z \amp = \frac{\ee^{z}+\ee^{-z}}{2} = \cosh x \cos y + \ii\sinh x\sin y</mrow>
      </md>

      <p>
        Relationships between trigonometirc and hyperbolic functions:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\sin \ii z \amp = \ii \sinh z \amp \cos \ii z \amp = \cosh z</mrow>
        <mrow>\sinh \ii z \amp = \ii \sin z \amp \cosh \ii z \amp = \cos z</mrow>
      </md>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Logarithmic function:
        <me>
          \ln z=\ln|z|+\ii\arg z
        </me>
        Because the exponential function is periodic, its inverse must be multivalued.
        We can restrict it to arrive at the principal value
        <me>
          \Ln z=\ln|z|+\ii\Arg z
        </me>
        Here, we use the principal argument with <m>-\uppi&#x3C;\Arg z\le\uppi</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Complex powers:
        <aside>
          <p>
            Some exponent and root laws don’t carry over to complex numbers because of this!
          </p>
        </aside>
        <me>
          z^{\alpha}=\ee^{\alpha\ln z}
        </me>
        The principal value is <m>z^{\alpha}=\ee^{\alpha\Ln z}</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Inverse trigonometric functions etc.
        can also be arrived at in terms of exponentials.
        For example:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\sin\inv z \amp = -\ii\ln\qty(\ii z+(1-z^2)^{1/2})</mrow>
        <mrow>\cos\inv z \amp = -\ii\ln\qty(z+\ii (1-z^2)^{1/2})</mrow>
        <mrow>\tan\inv z \amp = \frac{\ii}{2}\ln\qty(\frac{\ii+z}{\ii-z})</mrow>
        <mrow>\sinh\inv z \amp = \ln\qty(z+(z^2+1)^{1/2})</mrow>
        <mrow>\cosh\inv z \amp = \ln\qty(z+(z^2-1)^{1/2})</mrow>
        <mrow>\tanh\inv z \amp = \frac{1}{2}\ln\qty(\frac{1+z}{1-z})</mrow>
      </md>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Brief look at Riemann surfaces <mdash/> just enough to show where the “rest” of the function is for the functions with branch cuts.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
